Specialty Lesson: Shiny things in R

Shiny: Introduction

Shiny is an R package that makes it easy to build interactive web applications (apps) straight from R.

Before we go any further, lets install the shiny package.

Additional lessons and info from Shiny Tutorial

install.packages("shiny")

Structure of a Shiny App

Shiny apps are contained in a single script called app.R

app.R has three components:

  • a user interface object

  • a server function

  • a call to the shinyApp function

The user interface (ui) object controls the layout and appearance of your app.

  • think of this like the body of a car

The server function contains the instructions that your computer needs to build your app.

  • this is like the engine underneath the hood of the car

Finally the shinyApp function creates Shiny app objects from an explicit UI/server pair.

  • this is the link between the engine and the rest of the car like the belts, pistons, wires

Lets check out an example app by running the following:

library(shiny)
runExample("01_hello")

So lets break down what we see.

We will start with the ui.

Before we begin lets copy and paste the code from the running app. Save it as app.R so R studio can recognize your code as an app. You can add anything before but it must end with app.R. When we do this we will see a new button Run App with a play button appear on the top right of our R script. We will also see a blue button appear that would publish your application to a RStudio Connect Server. This is how we allow other Pfizer colleagues to access our applications.

UI

The first thing we see is fluidPage. This sets up our ui as a grid with rows and columns. This allows us to move and display things based on x and y by selecting row and column numbers. The apps are set to a 12-wide grid system meaning 1 will be the furthest left and 12 will be the farthest right.

fluidPage(

Next we see is titlePanel. This one is fairly self explanatory. Adds a title to the app. In this example we call it Hello Shiny!.

titlePanel("Hello Shiny!")

Now we can set what type of app layout design we want. A popular layout is sidebarLayout. This is what creates a simple sidebar on the left or right side of the app(add option position = right). You can also create a custom layout using fluidRow and column without setting up a layout and using the grid system. Other options include tabsetPanel, which creates an app with tabs and navlistPanel, which combines tabs into a sidebar panel layout. The final options is navbarPage which is useful for combining multiple tabs that each have their own individual sub-components.

sidebarLayout(

Within sidebarLayout we have 2 working areas. sidebarPanel and the mainPanel. Basically anything enclosed within the sidebarPanel will appear in that area and anything within the mainpanel will be displayed in the respective area.

Under the sidebarPanel we see our first control widget of a slider. More control widgets can be seen here

Note: How do you know what widgets are available, how to create them, and their options? Google away!!!

Lets dive into the slider. You can set up a slider with sliderInput.

sliderInput(

How can we find out what options are available to us besides google?

Try typing sliderInput into your rscript or console and hitting tab.

inputId: allows us to use this as an input for another function. We can call it by using input$name of inputId.

label: title or label of slider

min: min value of slider

max: max value of slider

value: starting (set) value of slider

In our mainPanel we see a single histogram that we render using plotOutput. Type into your console and check out the options available.

Our plotOutput has an outputId. As opposed to the inputId this option is looking for an output from another function. We can call it by using the name of the output object we set in the server or other location.

Server

We set our server function with an input and output. This allows us to input variables from our UI and output variables to our UI.

We start by creating an output variable. We do this by typing output$outputvariablename.

Then we tell the server what we want to do with the output. In this case we are using renderPlot. We can also renderPrint, renderTable, and create reactive elements that can be used in other functions but do not render anything in the ui (conductors).

Based off what you have learned so far throughout the coding classes, what is going on within the renderPlot?

Check out faithful dataset and new x variable.

Change input$bins to a value (say 25) and run everthing underneath renderplot function.

Why do we use plus 1? Breaks are the cutoff at each bar and not the bar themselves so we need to add 1 more break if we are to get the true value of our slider.

output$distPlot <- renderPlot({

    x    <- faithful$waiting
    bins <- seq(min(x), max(x), length.out = input$bins + 1)

    hist(x, breaks = bins, col = "#75AADB", border = "white",
         xlab = "Waiting time to next eruption (in mins)",
         main = "Histogram of waiting times")

    })

This output of distPlot is fed an input of our slider in the sidebarPanel and outputs the histogram to our mainpanel.

Tabset panel

This example has tabs within a mainPanel but we could certainly have an app that is soley tabs.

tabsetPanel(type = "tabs",
                  tabPanel("Plot", plotOutput("plot")),
                  tabPanel("Summary", verbatimTextOutput("summary")),
                  tabPanel("Table", tableOutput("table"))
      )

verbatimTextOutput is the receiver from renderPrint.

Here is our first look at a reactive function call.

d <- reactive({
    dist <- switch(input$dist,
                   norm = rnorm,
                   unif = runif,
                   lnorm = rlnorm,
                   exp = rexp,
                   rnorm)

    dist(input$n)
  })

We also have our first look at a switch which means a different value will be selected based on the selection it correponds to. In this example different distribution types (stats) are run based on the selection on the sidebarPanel. Ex: Normal -> norm -> rnorm

We then run the stats on the input$n (whatever the slider value is). This reactive value is set to d.It needs to be reactive because it appears in multiple functions. d() is now output of stats selected in the sidebarpanel on the value in the slider.

We then move to our output$plot. What do we know? Where is the reactive element and how do we call it d()?
